AUDIO: 'to do. So some of the built-in ones include, for example, help. This will show you all of the different commands that you\'re able to use. As you can see here, we\'ve got a bunch of the different inbuilt ones that we can use as well.'

[09:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What this will do is have a specific instruction that Claude can run. Now, as you start chatting through with Claude Code, what you\'ll find is there\'s something called the context window. When you first start talking to it, it\'s'

[09:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to have a really amount of information that it\'s stored readily available for that conversation. But as you chat more and more and more, it\'s going to be storing more of that information to use and reference in the'

[09:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'future. Now, we\'re going to have two commands to help deal with this. We\'re going to be able to do forward slash and then compact, which is going to keep the conversation history, but it\'s going to'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'summarize all of this information so we can use some of it in the future conversations. The other way, if you really want to open it up, is just to come through and do claim, and this will literally remove any of that'

[10:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'conversation that you\'ve had up to date and free up that entire context window for you to continue on. And that will stop that context window getting full and leading to what we call context rot. This is where the output start getting'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worse and worse and worse because it becomes overwhelmed with all the information. It starts losing sight of what you\'re trying to achieve, the outputs you\'re trying to get. And to check the amount of context, you can go through and just type context in here,'

[10:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and you\'ll be able to see the total context usage for this current conversation at the moment. But what if you having a previous conversation with Claude and you wanted to bring it back? Well, you\'re able to do forward slash'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'resume. This is then going to resume a previous conversation that you had so that you can actually continue it nice and easily. So if you do forward slash and then resume, and if you just press enter, now you\'ll be able to see the'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different conversations that you had in the past so you can press enter and bring it back into that conversation forward like you\'ve never left it. Next up is cost, and that all comes down to two main different ways that we\'re able'

