[22:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'businesses, you don\'t just live in one system. They all need to be able to talk to each other. You need to be able to access data from different ones and pull it through to complete processes. If we come across to the official'

[22:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'documentation for MCP servers with Claude code, you\'ll see here that we\'ve got lots of different popular ones and just the simple command to install them. I\'ll include all of the links down below so you can find this nice and easily and'

[23:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you wanted to install a brand new one for example Bitly, just come through and copy this command here, open up a new terminal on your machine, paste in there and now it\'s going to go through and add'

[23:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that specific MCP ability to our Claude code instance across all of our projects. Now, everything so far we\'ve been running within one single conversation, but there\'s a feature that\'s really important to understand'

[23:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called sub agents. What this enables us to do is in our main conversation is going to be our main AI agent, but say we need to complete multiple different deliverables, multiple different outputs'

[23:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for one specific task. Well, then what we\'re able to do is A, create our very own agents which I\'ll show you in a second, but we can get it to go through and complete specific outputs. So, maybe you need one to be a researcher to'

[23:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'investigate a specific market awareness around a tool. Then maybe we\'re developing a new app, a new feature. We can go through and use the tester and the developer both for different lenses to see if we\'re actually getting the'

[24:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'best outputs. And then last but not least, say we\'re doing some LinkedIn copywriting, again we could have our very own sub writing agent to complete that specific task. Each one is going to run with its own context window. It\'s'

[24:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to help get us better outputs and we\'re able to run them in parallel so it speeds up that development versus having just one conversation running with our main AI agent at any one time. Think of it as having sub agents as specialist'

[24:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where we\'ve got our main agent as the coordinator and generalist to get your outputs. But, Anthropic have also taken this one step further because we\'ve now got what\'s called agent teams. Now, previously with sub agents, they\'re not'

[24:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually able to talk to each other throughout the process. You send off one piece of information and it sends it back once it\'s done. What we can do with agent teams which do use a lot more'

[25:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tokens as a result is they\'re able to have context around what each other\'s doing so they understand for example if we\'re changing the API, how would we then need to test them, but also they can work with our main agent in a'

[25:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coordinated way to say how we would need to update any of the tasks we\'re completing, adding any relevant of course context to help get the output and much, much more. But, it does come'

[25:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at that token cost which will mean that you run into a limit a lot quicker and I would only recommend it for really complex build or lots of complex changes where they all interconnect with each other. If you\'re getting it to go'

